The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Hyderabad, Feb. 9: The Andhra Pradesh government has decided to order a CBI investigation into the Rs 7,000-crore accounting fraud in Satyam. Chief minister Y.S. Rajasekhara Reddy has sent a letter to the Prime Minister recommending the investigation. Meanwhile, a local court has admitted a number of petitions filed by Sebi and the income tax department seeking permission to quiz the Satyam fraud accused.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 9: Pressure is mounting on the government to deregulate fuel prices, with crude ruling at $40 a barrel. The time is ripe for ending state control on fuel prices as the international rates of crude have fallen, said Suresh Tendulkar, chairman of the Prime Ministers economic advisory council.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 9: Fitch has retained Indias credit rating at lowest investment grade in both international and domestic markets. Fitch Ratings has affirmed Indias long-term foreign currency and local currency Issuer Default Rating at BBB-, the agency said.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 9: Sahara India Power Corporation will set up a 1,320 MW thermal power project at Balangir in Orissa at an investment of Rs 5,604 crore. The first unit of 660 MW capacity will be commissioned in four years.                             
	 Calcutta, Feb. 9: The ongoing economic slowdown has rendered 40,000-50,000 people jobless in the foundry sector in Bengal, Ravi Sehgal, president of the Institute of Indian Foundrymen said. Out of 300 units, 60 has been closed.                                                                                                                           
